[{"_1":2},"routes/puzzle-detail",{"_3":4},"data",{"_5":6,"_7":8},"slug","twin-primes-unsolved","puzzle",{"_5":6,"_9":10,"_32":33,"_34":35,"_36":37},"metadata",{"_11":12,"_13":14,"_15":16,"_20":21,"_22":23,"_26":27,"_28":27,"_29":30,"_31":30},"id","31","title","Twin Primes: The Infinite Question","concepts",[17,18,19],"number-theory","primes","conjectures","difficulty","open","tags",[21,24,25],"fundamental","prime-patterns","dateCreated","2025-10-22T00:00:00.000Z","lastUpdated","preview","Twin Primes Twin primes are pairs of primes that differ by exactly 2. Examples : (3, 5) (5, 7) (11, 13) (17, 19) (29, 31) (41, 43) ... (2,003,663,613 ×...","websitePreview","content","<h2 class=\"markdown-h1\">Twin Primes</h2>\n<p><strong>Twin primes</strong> are pairs of primes that differ by exactly 2.</p>\n<p><strong>Examples</strong>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>(3, 5)</li>\n<li>(5, 7)</li>\n<li>(11, 13)</li>\n<li>(17, 19)</li>\n<li>(29, 31)</li>\n<li>(41, 43)</li>\n<li>...</li>\n<li>(2,003,663,613 × 2^195,000 - 1, 2,003,663,613 × 2^195,000 + 1) — with 58,711 digits each!</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 class=\"markdown-h1\">The Twin Prime Conjecture</h2>\n<p><strong>Conjecture</strong>: There are infinitely many twin prime pairs.</p>\n<p>This was first stated explicitly by Alphonse de Polignac in 1846, though it was likely considered earlier. Despite 179 years of effort, it remains unproven.</p>\n<h2 class=\"markdown-h1\">The Research Challenge</h2>\n<p>This is an <strong>open research problem</strong> at the frontier of number theory.</p>\n<p><strong>Computational evidence</strong>: Millions of twin prime pairs have been found, with the largest having tens of thousands of digits. They appear to continue indefinitely.</p>\n<p><strong>Your challenge</strong>: Explore what's known and what remains mysterious:</p>\n<p><strong>Part A</strong>: Explain why (3, 5) is the only twin prime pair where both primes are consecutive integers (differ by 2) and one of them is even.</p>\n<p><strong>Part B</strong>: Use the Prime Number Theorem to estimate how many twin prime pairs should exist below one million. Compare your estimate with the actual count: 8,169 pairs. How accurate is the heuristic?</p>\n<p><strong>Part C</strong>: Research Zhang's breakthrough (2013) on bounded gaps between primes. What did Zhang prove, and why was it revolutionary even though it didn't prove the twin prime conjecture?</p>\n<p><strong>Part D</strong>: Explain the Polymath project that followed Zhang's work. How did collaborative mathematics push Zhang's bound from 70,000,000 down to 246?</p>\n<p><strong>Part E</strong>: Research the <strong>Hardy-Littlewood conjecture</strong> about twin prime density. What does it predict about how twin primes thin out as numbers grow larger?</p>\n<p><strong>Part F</strong>: Propose why the twin prime conjecture is harder to prove than the infinitude of primes. What makes a gap of exactly 2 so much harder to guarantee than merely finding infinitely many primes?</p>\n<details class=\"hint-block\" data-type=\"hint\"><summary class=\"hint-label\">Hint</summary><div class=\"hint-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p>For Part A, consider what \"consecutive integers differ by 2\" means. The only consecutive integers differing by 2 are like (n, n+2) where one must be even.</p></div></details>\n<details class=\"hint-block\" data-type=\"hint\"><summary class=\"hint-label\">Hint</summary><div class=\"hint-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p>For Part B, use probability heuristics. If a number near n is prime with probability 1/ln(n), what's the probability that both n and n+2 are prime?</p></div></details>\n<details class=\"hint-block\" data-type=\"hint\"><summary class=\"hint-label\">Hint</summary><div class=\"hint-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p>For Part C, Zhang proved infinitely many gaps ≤ 70,000,000. This was the first finite bound ever proven.</p></div></details>\n<details class=\"hint-block\" data-type=\"hint\"><summary class=\"hint-label\">Hint</summary><div class=\"hint-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p>For Part E, Hardy-Littlewood predicted π₂(x) ~ 2C₂ ∫ dt/(ln t)², where C₂ ≈ 0.66 is the twin prime constant.</p></div></details>\n<details class=\"solution-block\" data-type=\"solution\"><summary class=\"solution-label\">Solution</summary><div class=\"solution-content markdown-content prose max-w-none px-4 py-4 space-y-4\"><p><strong>Answer</strong>: This problem is unsolved. Below are investigations and current understanding.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part A: Why (3, 5) Is Special</h3><p>The question asks about twin primes where both primes are consecutive integers.</p><p><strong>Clarification</strong>: Twin primes are primes that differ by 2, like (p, p+2). They are not consecutive integers in general (e.g., 11 and 13 are not consecutive integers; 12 is between them).</p><p><strong>However</strong>, among integers, consecutive odd numbers differ by 2:</p><ul>\n<li>1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, ...</li>\n</ul><p>So the question might be asking: why is (3, 5) the only twin prime pair including an even prime?</p><p><strong>Answer</strong>: 2 is the only even prime. For any twin prime pair (p, p+2):</p><ul>\n<li>If p = 2, then p+2 = 4, which is not prime</li>\n<li>If p > 2, then p is odd, so p+2 is also odd</li>\n</ul><p>Therefore, all twin prime pairs except possibly those involving 2 consist of two odd primes.</p><p>For (3, 5): 3 is odd and 5 is odd, but this is \"close\" to involving 2.</p><p>The truly special aspect of (3, 5):</p><ul>\n<li>(2, 3) is NOT a twin prime pair (they differ by 1)</li>\n<li>(3, 5) IS a twin prime pair</li>\n<li>This is the smallest twin prime pair and the only one involving single-digit primes close to the even prime 2</li>\n</ul><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part B: Heuristic Estimate</h3><p>By the Prime Number Theorem, the probability a number near x is prime is approximately 1/ln(x).</p><p><strong>Naive heuristic</strong>: If we assume independence, the probability that both n and n+2 are prime would be:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mo fence=\"true\">(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo fence=\"true\">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\left(\\frac{1}{\\ln x}\\right)^2 = \\frac{1}{(\\ln x)^2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.404em;vertical-align:-0.35em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"minner\"><span class=\"mopen delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">(</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.345em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mclose delimcenter\" style=\"top:0em;\"><span class=\"delimsizing size1\">)</span></span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.054em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.3029em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3651em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>The expected number of twin prime pairs up to x:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≈</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msubsup><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>t</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_2(x) \\approx \\int_2^x \\frac{1}{(\\ln t)^2} dt</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.3793em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8593em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3442em;margin-left:-0.1945em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2579em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3558em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8451em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span></p><p>For x = 1,000,000:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≈</mo><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></msubsup><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>t</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_2(10^6) \\approx \\int_2^{10^6} \\frac{dt}{(\\ln t)^2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.7018em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.1818em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3442em;margin-left:-0.1945em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2579em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\