ass=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.5379em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.0179em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8913em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.931em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">correction factor</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8389em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">8</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span></span><span class=\"mord\">000</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Actual count</strong>: π₂(1,000,000) = <strong>8,169</strong></p><p>The refined heuristic is remarkably accurate! This gives strong evidence that twin primes continue indefinitely, following predictable density patterns.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part C: Zhang's Breakthrough</h3><p><strong>Yitang Zhang (2013)</strong>: Proved that there are <strong>infinitely many pairs of primes that differ by at most 70,000,000</strong>.</p><p>More precisely: there exists at least one even integer h ≤ 70,000,000 such that there are infinitely many prime pairs (p, p+h).</p><p><strong>Why this was revolutionary</strong>:</p><ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>First finite bound</strong>: Before Zhang, no one had proved a finite bound on gaps. This was the first time anyone proved infinitely many primes have \"small\" (finite) gaps between them.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Unexpected source</strong>: Zhang was not a well-known number theorist. He was working part-time jobs after years away from academia when he made this breakthrough.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Proof technique</strong>: Zhang combined ideas from sieve theory, exponential sums, and understanding of Siegel zeros in novel ways.</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Psychological breakthrough</strong>: Showed the problem was attackable, inspiring the mathematical community.</p>\n</li>\n</ol><p><strong>Why it didn't prove twin primes</strong>: Zhang's bound of 70,000,000 is much larger than 2. To prove the twin prime conjecture, we need to show h = 2 works, not just h ≤ 70,000,000.</p><p>But Zhang showed that <strong>some</strong> bounded gap occurs infinitely often. Getting from 70,000,000 down to 2 is \"just\" a matter of improving the bound.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part D: The Polymath Project</h3><p>Immediately after Zhang's announcement, Terence Tao organised <strong>Polymath8</strong>, a collaborative online project to improve Zhang's bound.</p><p><strong>Timeline</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li><strong>May 2013</strong>: Zhang announces bound of 70,000,000</li>\n<li><strong>June 2013</strong>: Polymath8 begins</li>\n<li><strong>July 2013</strong>: Bound reduced to 4,680</li>\n<li><strong>November 2013</strong>: James Maynard (independently) and Polymath8 both reach bound of 600</li>\n<li><strong>April 2014</strong>: Assuming the <strong>Elliott-Halberstam conjecture</strong> (unproven), bound reduced to <strong>6</strong></li>\n<li><strong>Final unconditional bound</strong>: <strong>246</strong></li>\n</ul><p><strong>How it worked</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li>Hundreds of mathematicians worldwide contributed</li>\n<li>Real-time collaboration via blogs and forums</li>\n<li>Rapid peer review and idea exchange</li>\n<li>Combined Zhang's methods with new sieve theory techniques</li>\n</ul><p><strong>Key insight</strong>: Zhang had been conservative in some estimates. By carefully optimising his approach and incorporating new ideas (especially from Maynard), the bound plummeted.</p><p><strong>Current status</strong>: Unconditionally, we know infinitely many prime gaps ≤ 246. Assuming Elliott-Halberstam, infinitely many gaps ≤ 6.</p><p>But proving infinitely many gaps = 2 (the twin prime conjecture) remains out of reach.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part E: Hardy-Littlewood Conjecture</h3><p>The <strong>Hardy-Littlewood conjecture</strong> (1923) predicts the density of twin primes:</p><p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∼</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi></msubsup><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>t</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_2(x) \\sim 2C_2 \\int_2^x \\frac{dt}{(\\ln t)^2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.4001em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"margin-right:0.19445em;position:relative;top:-0.0006em;\">∫</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8593em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.3442em;margin-left:-0.1945em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.2579em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3558em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8801em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">d</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">t</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p>where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is the <strong>twin prime constant</strong>:</p><p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>∏</mo><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mfrac><mrow><mi>p</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>≈</mo><mn>0.6601618158...</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C_2 = \\prod_{p \\geq 3} \\frac{p(p-2)}{(p-1)^2} \\approx 0.6601618158...</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.53em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop op-symbol small-op\" style=\"position:relative;top:0em;\">∏</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span><span class=\"mrel mtight\">≥</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">3</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.4358em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.01em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.485em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span><span class=\"mbin mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0.6601618158...</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Asymptotic form</strong>:\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∼</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\pi_2(x) \\sim 2C_2 \\frac{x}{(\\ln x)^2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">π</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0359em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.2154em;vertical-align:-0.52em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:-0.0715em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mopen nulldelimiter\"></span><span class=\"mfrac\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6954em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.655em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">(</span><span class=\"mop mtight\"><span class=\"mtight\">l</span><span class=\"mtight\">n</span></span><span class=\"mspace mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.1952em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\"><span class=\"mclose mtight\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7463em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.786em;margin-right:0.0714em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.5em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size3 size1 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.23em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"frac-line\" style=\"border-bottom-width:0.04em;\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.394em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">x</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.52em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose nulldelimiter\"></span></span></span></span></span></p><p><strong>Interpretation</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li>Twin primes become rarer as numbers grow</li>\n<li>The density decreases as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>ln</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mi>x</mi><msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1/(\\ln x)^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0641em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1/</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mop\">ln</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mclose\"><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>\n<li>But since this decreases slower than <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1/x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>, there are infinitely many (if the conjecture is true)</li>\n</ul><p><strong>Comparison with all primes</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li>π(x) ~ x/ln(x) (Prime Number Theorem)</li>\n<li>π₂(x) ~ x/(ln x)² (Hardy-Littlewood conjecture)</li>\n</ul><p>Twin primes are \"rarer\" than primes by an additional factor of ln(x).</p><p><strong>Computational evidence</strong>: The Hardy-Littlewood formula matches observed twin prime counts with remarkable precision, supporting the twin prime conjecture.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">Part F: Why It's Harder Than Infinitude of Primes</h3><p>Euclid proved infinitely many primes exist around 300 BCE. Why can't we prove infinitely many twin primes exist?</p><p><strong>Euclid's proof</strong> (simplified):</p><ul>\n<li>Assume finitely many primes: p₁, p₂, ..., pₙ</li>\n<li>Consider N = p₁p₂...pₙ + 1</li>\n<li>N is not divisible by any pᵢ</li>\n<li>Therefore, N has a prime factor not in our list</li>\n<li>Contradiction ∎</li>\n</ul><p>This works because:</p><ol>\n<li><strong>Additive construction</strong>: We can always construct a number with new prime factors</li>\n<li><strong>No constraint on gaps</strong>: We don't care how far apart primes are</li>\n</ol><p><strong>Twin prime difficulty</strong>:</p><ol>\n<li><strong>Gap constraint</strong>: We need primes exactly 2 apart</li>\n<li><strong>Local density</strong>: It's not enough to show primes exist; we need them appearing in pairs with specific spacing</li>\n<li><strong>Multiplicative structure vs additive constraint</strong>: Primes are defined multiplicatively (indivisible) but twin primes require additive structure (p and p+2 both prime)</li>\n</ol><p><strong>Existing proof attempts</strong>:</p><ul>\n<li><strong>Sieve methods</strong> (like Chen's theorem) can show \"almost twin primes\" but can't enforce exact primality of both members</li>\n<li><strong>Zhang/Maynard/Polymath</strong> show bounded gaps exist but can't reduce to gap = 2</li>\n<li><strong>Circle method</strong> gives heuristics but can't make them rigorous</li>\n</ul><p><strong>The fundamental obstacle</strong>: We don't understand the local structure of primes well enough. We know their global density (Prime Number Theorem) but not their fine-scale spacing.</p><p><strong>Analogy</strong>: Proving infinitely many primes is like proving a forest continues forever. Proving infinitely many twin primes is like proving specific types of trees appear side-by-side infinitely often. The latter requires much deeper understanding of the forest's structure.</p><h3 class=\"markdown-h2\">The Path Forward</h3><p>Active research directions:</p><ol>\n<li><strong>Improve bounded gaps</strong>: Get from 246 down to 2</li>\n<li><strong>Prove Elliott-Halberstam conjecture</strong>: Would improve bounds dramatically</li>\n<li><strong>Develop new sieve techniques</strong>: Go beyond current limitations</li>\n<li><strong>Connect to other conjectures</strong>: Links to Goldbach, Riemann Hypothesis</li>\n</ol><p>The twin prime conjecture stands as a testament to how much we still don't understand about prime numbers, despite centuries of study.</p></div></details>","rawContent","\n# Twin Primes\n\n**Twin primes** are pairs of primes that differ by exactly 2.\n\n**Examples**:\n- (3, 5)\n- (5, 7)\n- (11, 13)\n- (17, 19)\n- (29, 31)\n- (41, 43)\n- ...\n- (2,003,663,613 × 2^195,000 - 1, 2,003,663,613 × 2^195,000 + 1) — with 58,711 digits each!\n\n# The Twin Prime Conjecture\n\n**Conjecture**: There are infinitely many twin prime pairs.\n\nThis was first stated explicitly by Alphonse de Polignac in 1846, though it was likely considered earlier. Despite 179 years of effort, it remains unproven.\n\n# The Research Challenge\n\nThis is an **open research problem** at the frontier of number theory.\n\n**Computational evidence**: Millions of twin prime pairs have been found, with the largest having tens of thousands of digits. They appear to continue indefinitely.\n\n**Your challenge**: Explore what's known and what remains mysterious:\n\n**Part A**: Explain why (3, 5) is the only twin prime pair where both primes are consecutive integers (differ by 2) and one of them is even.\n\n**Part B**: Use the Prime Number Theorem to estimate how many twin prime pairs should exist below one million. Compare your estimate with the actual count: 8,169 pairs. How accurate is the heuristic?\n\n**Part C**: Research Zhang's breakthrough (2013) on bounded gaps between primes. What did Zhang prove, and why was it revolutionary even though it didn't prove the twin prime conjecture?\n\n**Part D**: Explain the Polymath project that followed Zhang's work. How did collaborative mathematics push Zhang's bound from 70,000,000 down to 246?\n\n**Part E**: Research the **Hardy-Littlewood conjecture** about twin prime density. What does it predict about how twin primes thin out as numbers grow larger?\n\n**Part F**: Propose why the twin prime conjecture is harder to prove than the infinitude of primes. What makes a gap of exactly 2 so much harder to guarantee than merely finding infinitely many primes?\n\n:::hint\nFor Part A, consider what \"consecutive integers differ by 2\" means. The only consecutive integers differing by 2 are like (n, n+2) where one must be even.\n:::\n\n:::hint\nFor Part B, use probability heuristics. If a number near n is prime with probability 1/ln(n), what's the probability that both n and n+2 are prime?\n:::\n\n:::hint\nFor Part C, Zhang proved infinitely many gaps ≤ 70,000,000. This was the first finite bound ever proven.\n:::\n\n:::hint\nFor Part E, Hardy-Littlewood predicted π₂(x) ~ 2C₂ ∫ dt/(ln t)², where C₂ ≈ 0.66 is the twin prime constant.\n:::\n\n:::solution\n**Answer**: This problem is unsolved. Below are investigations and current understanding.\n\n## Part A: Why (3, 5) Is Special\n\nThe question asks about twin primes where both primes are consecutive integers.\n\n**Clarification**: Twin primes are primes that differ by 2, like (p, p+2). They are not consecutive integers in general (e.g., 11 and 13 are not consecutive integers; 12 is between them).\n\n**However**, among integers, consecutive odd numbers differ by 2:\n- 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, ...\n\nSo the question might be asking: why is (3, 5) the only twin prime pair including an even prime?\n\n**Answer**: 2 is the only even prime. For any twin prime pair (p, p+2):\n- If p = 2, then p+2 = 4, which is not prime\n- If p > 2, then p is odd, so p+2 is also odd\n\nTherefore, all twin prime pairs except possibly those involving 2 consist of two odd primes.\n\nFor (3, 5): 3 is odd and 5 is odd, but this is \"close\" to involving 2.\n\nThe truly special aspect of (3, 5):\n- (2, 3) is NOT a twin prime pair (they differ by 1)\n- (3, 5) IS a twin prime pair\n- This is the smallest twin prime pair and the only one involving single-digit primes close to the even prime 2\n\n## Part B: Heuristic Estimate\n\nBy the Prime Number Theorem, the probability a number near x is prime is approximately 1/ln(x).\n\n**Naive heuristic**: If we assume independence, the probability that both n and n+2 are prime would be:\n$$\\left(\\frac{1}{\\ln x}\\right)^2 = \\frac{1}{(\\ln x)^2}$$\n\nThe expected number of twin prime pairs up to x:\n$$\\pi_2(x) \\approx \\int_2^x \\frac{1}{(\\ln t)^2} dt$$\n\nFor x = 1,000,000:\n$$\\pi_2(10^6) \\approx \\int_2^{10^6} \\frac{dt}{(\\ln t)^2}$$\n\nThis integral doesn't have a simple closed form, but we can approximate:\n$$\\approx \\frac{x}{(\\ln x)^2} \\times 2 \\approx \\frac{10^6}{(13.8)^2} \\times 2 \\approx \\frac{2 \\times 10^6}{190} \\approx 10{,}500$$\n\n**However**, this is too crude. The **Hardy-Littlewood conjecture** refines this with the twin prime constant C₂ ≈ 0.66:\n$$\\pi_2(x) \\sim 2C_2 \\int_2^x \\frac{dt}{(\\ln t)^2}$$\n\nBetter approximation for x = 1,000,000:\n$$\\pi_2(10^6) \\approx 2 \\times 0.66 \\times \\frac{10^6}{(\\ln 10^6)^2} \\times \\text{correction factor} \\approx 8{,}000$$\n\n**Actual count**: π₂(1,000,000) = **8,169**\n\nThe refined heuristic is remarkably accurate! This gives strong evidence that twin primes continue indefinitely, following predictable density patterns.\n\n## Part C: Zhang's Breakthrough\n\n**Yitang Zhang (2013)**: Proved that there are **infinitely many pairs of primes that differ by at most 70,000,000**.\n\nMore precisely: there exists at least one even integer h ≤ 70,000,000 such that there are infinitely many prime pairs (p, p+h).\n\n**Why this was revolutionary**:\n\n1. **First finite bound**: Before Zhang, no one had proved a finite bound on gaps. This was the first time anyone proved infinitely many primes have \"small\" (finite) gaps between them.\n\n2. **Unexpected source**: Zhang was not a well-known number theorist. He was working part-time jobs after years away from academia when he made this breakthrough.\n\n3. **Proof technique**: Zhang combined ideas from sieve theory, exponential sums, and understanding of Siegel zeros in novel ways.\n\n4. **Psychological breakthrough**: Showed the problem was attackable, inspiring the mathematical community.\n\n**Why it didn't prove twin primes**: Zhang's bound of 70,000,000 is much larger than 2. To prove the twin prime conjecture, we need to show h = 2 works, not just h ≤ 70,000,000.\n\nBut Zhang showed that **some** bounded gap occurs infinitely often. Getting from 70,000,000 down to 2 is \"just\" a matter of improving the bound.\n\n## Part D: The Polymath Project\n\nImmediately after Zhang's announcement, Terence Tao organised **Polymath8**, a collaborative online project to improve Zhang's bound.\n\n**Timeline**:\n- **May 2013**: Zhang announces bound of 70,000,000\n- **June 2013**: Polymath8 begins\n- **July 2013**: Bound reduced to 4,680\n- **November 2013**: James Maynard (independently) and Polymath8 both reach bound of 600\n- **April 2014**: Assuming the **Elliott-Halberstam conjecture** (unproven), bound reduced to **6**\n- **Final unconditional bound**: **246**\n\n**How it worked**:\n- Hundreds of mathematicians worldwide contributed\n- Real-time collaboration via blogs and forums\n- Rapid peer review and idea exchange\n- Combined Zhang's methods with new sieve theory techniques\n\n**Key insight**: Zhang had been conservative in some estimates. By carefully optimising his approach and incorporating new ideas (especially from Maynard), the bound plummeted.\n\n**Current status**: Unconditionally, we know infinitely many prime gaps ≤ 246. Assuming Elliott-Halberstam, infinitely many gaps ≤ 6.\n\nBut proving infinitely many gaps = 2 (the twin prime conjecture) remains out of reach.\n\n## Part E: Hardy-Littlewood Conjecture\n\nThe **Hardy-Littlewood conjecture** (1923) predicts the density of twin primes:\n\n$$\\pi_2(x) \\sim 2C_2 \\int_2^x \\frac{dt}{(\\ln t)^2}$$\n\nwhere $C_2$ is the **twin prime constant**:\n\n$$C_2 = \\prod_{p \\geq 3} \\frac{p(p-2)}{(p-1)^2} \\approx 0.6601618158...$$\n\n**Asymptotic form**:\n$$\\pi_2(x) \\sim 2C_2 \\frac{x}{(\\ln x)^2}$$\n\n**Interpretation**:\n- Twin primes become rarer as numbers grow\n- The density decreases as $1/(\\ln x)^2$\n- But since this decreases slower than $1/x$, there are infinitely many (if the conjecture is true)\n\n**Comparison with all primes**:\n- π(x) ~ x/ln(x) (Prime Number Theorem)\n- π₂(x) ~ x/(ln x)² (Hardy-Littlewood conjecture)\n\nTwin primes are \"rarer\" than primes by an additional factor of ln(x).\n\n**Computational evidence**: The Hardy-Littlewood formula matches observed twin prime counts with remarkable precision, supporting the twin prime conjecture.\n\n## Part F: Why It's Harder Than Infinitude of Primes\n\nEuclid proved infinitely many primes exist around 300 BCE. Why can't we prove infinitely many twin primes exist?\n\n**Euclid's proof** (simplified):\n- Assume finitely many primes: p₁, p₂, ..., pₙ\n- Consider N = p₁p₂...pₙ + 1\n- N is not divisible by any pᵢ\n- Therefore, N has a prime factor not in our list\n- Contradiction ∎\n\nThis works because:\n1. **Additive construction**: We can always construct a number with new prime factors\n2. **No constraint on gaps**: We don't care how far apart primes are\n\n**Twin prime difficulty**:\n1. **Gap constraint**: We need primes exactly 2 apart\n2. **Local density**: It's not enough to show primes exist; we need them appearing in pairs with specific spacing\n3. **Multiplicative structure vs additive constraint**: Primes are defined multiplicatively (indivisible) but twin primes require additive structure (p and p+2 both prime)\n\n**Existing proof attempts**:\n- **Sieve methods** (like Chen's theorem) can show \"almost twin primes\" but can't enforce exact primality of both members\n- **Zhang/Maynard/Polymath** show bounded gaps exist but can't reduce to gap = 2\n- **Circle method** gives heuristics but can't make them rigorous\n\n**The fundamental obstacle**: We don't understand the local structure of primes well enough. We know their global density (Prime Number Theorem) but not their fine-scale spacing.\n\n**Analogy**: Proving infinitely many primes is like proving a forest continues forever. Proving infinitely many twin primes is like proving specific types of trees appear side-by-side infinitely often. The latter requires much deeper understanding of the forest's structure.\n\n## The Path Forward\n\nActive research directions:\n1. **Improve bounded gaps**: Get from 246 down to 2\n2. **Prove Elliott-Halberstam conjecture**: Would improve bounds dramatically\n3. **Develop new sieve techniques**: Go beyond current limitations\n4. **Connect to other conjectures**: Links to Goldbach, Riemann Hypothesis\n\nThe twin prime conjecture stands as a testament to how much we still don't understand about prime numbers, despite centuries of study.\n:::\n","dynamicBlocks",[]]
